The User Module serves as the primary interface through which students, faculty, and other institutional stakeholders interact with the ISPSC Main E-Queue System. It encompasses all client-facing features designed to guide users from initial registration t
hrough ticket generation and real-time queue monitoring. The interface prioritizes clarity and ease of navigation to minimize user friction during high-traffic enrollment periods.
The system implements a multi-layered registration and authentication
protocol to ensure that only verified individuals gain access to the ticketing modules. During initial account creation, users are required to submit a valid institutional identifier — s

pecifically, their Student ID Number or Employee ID — along with a registered mobile number and an active email address. These credentials serve as the primary keys for account uniqueness validation within the system database,
To fortify access security, the system integrates a One-Time Password (OTP) verification mechanism. Upon successful submission of registration details, the
system automatically dispatches a six-digit OTP to the user's registered mobile
a secure SMS gateway. The OTP

carries a time-sensitive validity window of five (5) minutes, after which it expires and a new OTP must be requested. This time-bound mechanism prevents replay attacks and unauthorized access attempts

Upon successful OTP verification, the user's account is activated and a secure session token is generated, granting authenticated access to the system's core ticketing functionalities. The system also enforces strict password complex
a minimum of eight (8) characters, combining alphanumeric and special characters — to guard against brute-force vulnerabilities.
Additionally, account lockout policies are enforced after five (5) consecutive failed login attempts, tempor
arily suspending access to prevent unauthorized intrusion.

orresponding office, estimated processing duration, and current availability status.

documentation. Before a user can generate a ticket for specific academic or administrative services, the system displays a mandatory checklist of required documents. For example, a request for a Certificate of Enrollment typically requires the submission o
f: (1) a valid school ID, (2) an original official receipt of payment, and (3) a duly accomplished request form. The user must actively check
each item on the list, confirming possession of the required documents, before the "Generate Ticket" button is act

The Administrative Module provides privileged system access to authorized personnel, including office heads, queue managers, and institutional administrators. This module is designed to offer operational control, performance monitoring, and data governance
functionalities that support evidence-based institutional decision-
The system incorporates an executive-level analytics dashboard that consolidates service quality metrics across all campus offices. Centr

al to this dashboard is an AI-based sentiment analysis engine that processes user-submitted feedback collected after each completed service transaction. Users are prompted to submit a brief satisfaction response — either via a star rating or a short open-e

The sentiment analysis pipeline processes textual feedback through a Natural Language Processing (NLP) classification model that categorizes each response into one of three sentiment classes: Positive, Neutral, or Negati
ve. The model employs tokenization, stop-word filtering, and term-frequency analysis to extract sentiment polarity from raw text input. Results are aggregated in real time and visualized
through interactive charts, including a donut chart for sentiment dis
tribution, a time-series line graph for trend analysis, and a per-office performance heatmap.
Administrators can filter analytics by date range, office, service type, and sentiment class. This allows department heads to identify service quality trends, pin
point recurring issues, and make informed staffing and procedural adjustments.

In compliance with the Republic Act No. 10173, also known as the Data Privacy Act of 2012, and the National Privacy Commission's (NPC) guidelines on personal data processing, the ISPSC Main E-Queue System implements a data anonymization framework within it

s analytics pipeline. Specifically, all user-facing analytics reports and exported data files display Ticket Numbers as the primary identifier rather than full names, student ID numbers, or other directly identifiable personal information.

This pseudonymization approach ensures that sentiment scores, service duration records, and behavioral analytics remain operationally useful for administrative decision-making while simultaneously protecting individual user identities from exposure in shar
ed dashboards, printed reports, or exported files. The mapping between ticket numbers and actual user identities is maintained only in secured backend logs, accessible exclusively to the System
Administrator with audit-trail logging for every access event.
Furthermore, personal data collected during registration is encrypted at rest using AES-256 encryption standards and transmitted over HTTPS/TLS 1.3 protocols.
The system provides administrators with a robust report generation
module capable of producing institutional-grade data exports in three formats: Microsoft
Excel (.xlsx), Adobe PDF (.pdf), and Microsoft Word (.docx). Each export type is tailored
and statistical analysis, containing raw tabular data with column headers for Ticket Number, Service
Time, Processing Duration, Sentiment Score, and Sentiment Class.
PDF exports are formatted as formal printable repor

ts, complete with the institution's official letterhead, date stamps, summary statistics, and sentiment charts rendered as embedded graphics. Word exports follow a narrative report template, suitable for inclusion in formal institutional memoranda or board

-level presentations. All generated reports are logged in the system's export history, recording the requesting administrator's user ID, timestamp, and selected parameters for accountability and audit purposes.

The queue estimation engine employs a Constraint-Aware First-In, First-Out (CA-FIFO) algorithm specifically designed to account for the variable operational conditions present in a multi-office academic institution. Unlike standard FIFO
wait times solely based on queue length, the CA-FIFO algorithm incorporates a weighted multi-parameter model to produce statistically reliable estimated wait times.

The system interface is built on a mobile-first responsive design framework using CSS Flexbox and Grid layout systems. The layout adapts fluidly across three primary
s, the navigation collapses into a hamburger menu, ticket cards are rendered in single-column stacks, and touch-optimized tap targets (minimum 44×44px) are enforced throughout.

The ISPSC Main E-Queue System incorporates Web Content Accessibility Guidel

compliance features to ensure equitable access for users with disabilities. All interactive elements include ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) labels and roles, enabling screen reader compatibility for visually impaired
users. Color contrast ratios across all text-background combinations meet or exceed the WCAG minimum threshold of 4.5:1 for normal text and 3:1 for large text.
Form inputs include visible focus indicators and descriptive error messages to assist users with

cognitive or motor impairments. The system also supports keyboard-only navigation, allowing full system traversal without mouse interaction. Font sizes are defined in relative units (rem), enabling browser-level text scaling without layout breakage. These
accessibility provisions reflect the institution's commitment to inclusive educational services for all members of the ISPSC community.
